ition\n! style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers}}\"|Tenure\n|-\n| 14 || [[Johnny Unitas]] || QB || 1955\n|-\n| 36 || [[Marion Motley]] || RB || 1955\n|-\n| 52 || [[Mike Webster]] || C || 1974\u201388\n|-\n| 36 || [[Cal Hubbard]] || T || 1936\n|-\n| 75 || [[Joe Greene (American football)|Joe Greene]] || DT || 1969\u201381\n|-\n| 58 || [[Jack Lambert (American football)|Jack Lambert]] || LB || 1974\u201384\n|-\n| 59 || [[Jack Ham]] || LB || 1971\u201382\n|-\n| 47 || [[Mel Blount]] || CB || 1970\u201383\n|-\n| 26 || [[Rod Woodson]] || CB || 1987\u201396\n|-\n| \u2014 || [[Chuck Noll]] || Coach || 1969\u201391\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n=== All-time team ===\nIn {{Steelers season|2007}}, in celebration of the franchise's 75th season, the team announced an updated [[Pittsburgh Steelers All-Time Team|All-Time team]] of the 33 best players who have ever played for the Steelers.<ref name=\"PressRelease\">{{cite web|url=http://news.steelers.com/article/83505/|title=Steelers Announce All-Time Team as Part of Club's 75th Season Celebration|date=October 2007|publisher=Steelers.com|accessdate=March 19, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100304205254/http://news.steelers.com/article/83505|archivedate=March 4, 2010}}</ref>  This team supplanted the [[Pittsburgh Steelers All-Time Team (50th Season)|previous All-Time team]] of 24 players named as part of the 50th anniversary commemoration in {{Steelers season|1982}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/2007-10-24-2776242676_x.htm|title=1970s stars dominate Steelers all-time team|last=Robinson|first=Alan|date=October 24, 2007|work=USA Today|accessdate=March 19, 2010}}</ref>\n\nA [[Pittsburgh Steelers Legends team|\"Legends team\"]] consisting of the club's best pre-1970s players was released concurrently with the latest All-Time team.<ref name=\"LegendsPressRelease\">{{cite web|url=http://news.steelers.com/article/81289/|title=Steelers Announce Legends Team as Part of 75th Season Celebration Twenty-Four Honored as Best Pre-1970s Players in Club History|date=October 2007|publisher=Steelers.com|accessdate=March 22, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090605004004/http://news.steelers.com/article/81289/|archivedate=June 5, 2009}}</ref>\n\n{{Further|Pittsburgh Steelers All-Time Team}}\n\n=== Dapper Dan Sportsman of the Year ===\n{{unreferenced section|date=June 2017}}\nThe regional [[Dapper Dan Charities]] has since 1939 named the \"Sportsman of the Year\" in the Pittsburgh region. 19 Steelers have won the award in 23 events:\n*1941 Aldo Donelli\n*1942 Bill Dudley\n*1946 Bill Dudley\n*1950 Joe Geri\n*1952 Red Dawson\n*1955 John Michelosen\n*1962 Lou Michaels & John Michelosen\n*1968 Dick Hoak\n*1972 Chuck Noll\n*1974 Joe Greene\n*1975 Terry Bradshaw\n*1977 Franco Harris\n*1984 John Stallworth\n*1985 Louis Lipps\n*1992 Bill Cowher\n*1994 Bill Cowher\n*1997 Jerome Bettis\n*2001 Kordell Stewart\n*2004 Ben Roethlisberger\n*2005 Jerome Bettis\n*2008 Mike Tomlin\n*2014 Antonio Brown\n*2015 Antonio Brown\n*2018 James Conner\n\n== Hall of Honor ==\nThe Pittsburgh Steelers Hall of Honor was established on August 1, 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title=Steelers announce plans for Hall of Honor|url=http://www.steelers.com/news/article-1/Steelers-announce-plans-for-Hall-of-Honor/7150ef93-33ba-4401-ad2b-f5b4a50caada|publisher=Pittsburgh Steelers|date=August 1, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801165651/http://www.steelers.com/news/article-1/Steelers-announce-plans-for-Hall-of-Honor/7150ef93-33ba-4401-ad2b-f5b4a50caada|archivedate=August 1, 2017|accessdate=May 18, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> There have been 36 inductees.<ref name=\"Inaugural\">{{cite news|last=Varley|first=Teresa|title=Inaugural Hall of Honor class announced|url=http://www.steelers.com/news/article-1/Inaugural-Hall-of-Honor-class-announced/f6acccd2-c302-49b2-80b2-d4b4267fb285|publisher=Pittsburgh Steelers|date=August 29, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829174441/http://www.steelers.com/news/article-1/Inaugural-Hall-of-Honor-class-announced/f6acccd2-c302-49b2-80b2-d4b4267fb285|archivedate=August 29, 2017|accessdate=May 18, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Class of 2018\">{{cite news|last=Varley|first=Teresa|title=Steelers 2018 Hall of Honor Class revealed|url=https://www.steelers.com/news/steelers-2018-hall-of-honor-class-revealed|publisher=Pittsburgh Steelers|date=July 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Class of 2019\">{{cite news|last=Varley|first=Teresa|title=Four legends selected to Hall of Honor|url=https://www.steelers.com/news/four-legends-selected-to-hall-of-honor|publisher=Pittsburgh Steelers|date=July 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers}};\"|'''Pittsburgh Steelers Hall of Honor'''\n|-\n| style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers}};\"|'''N\u00b0'''\n| style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers}};\"|'''Name'''\n| style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers}};\"|'''Position '''\n| style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers}};\"|'''Years With Club'''\n| style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers}};\"|'''Inducted'''\n|-\n| 36 ||[[Jerome Bettis]] || RB || 1996\u20132005 || 2017<ref name=\"Inaugural\" />\n|-\n| 20 || [[Rocky Bleier]] || RB || 1968, 1970\u201380 || 2018<ref name=\"Class of 2018\" />\n|-\n| 47 || [[Mel Blount]] || CB || 1970\u201383 || 2017<ref name=\"Inaugural\" />\n|-\n| 12 || [[Terry Bradshaw]] || QB || 1970\u201383 || 2017<ref name=\"Inaugural\" />\n|-\n| 87<br />79<br /> || [[Larry Brown (tight end, born 1949)|Larry Brown]] || TE<br />OT<br /> || 1971\u201376<br />1977\u201384 <br /> || 2019<ref name=\"Class of 2019\" />\n|-\n| 80 || [[Jack Butler (American football)|Jack Butler]] || CB || 1951\u201359 || 2017<ref name=\"Inaugural\" />\n|-\n| \u2014 || [[Bill Cowher]] || Coach || 1992\u20132006 || 2019<ref name=\"Class of 2019\" />\n|-\n| 63 || [[Dermontti Dawson]] || C || 1988\u20132000 || 2017<ref name=\"Inaugural\" />\n|-\n| 84 || [[Buddy Dial]] || WR || 1959\u201363 || 2018<ref name=\"Class of 2018\" />\n|-\n| 35 || [[Bill Dudley]] || HB || 1942, 1945\u201346 || 2017<ref name=\"Inaugural\" />\n|-\n| 66 || [[Alan Faneca]] || G || 1998\u20132007 || 2018<ref name=\"Class of 2018\" />\n|-\n| 75 || [[Joe Greene]] || DT || 1969\u201381 || 2017<ref name=\"Inaugural\" />\n|-\n| 91 || [[Kevin Greene (American football)|Kevin Greene]] || LB || 1993\u201395 || 2017<ref name=\"Inaugural\" />\n|-\n| 68 || [[L.C. Greenwood]] || DE || 1969\u201381 || 2017<ref name=\"Inaugural\" />\n|-\n| 59 || [[Jack Ham]] || LB || 1971\u201382 || 2017<ref name=\"Inaugural\" />\n|-\n| 32 || [[Franco Harris]] || RB || 1972\u201383 || 2017<ref name=\"Inaugural\" />\n|-\n| 42 || [[Dick Hoak]] || RB<br />Coach<br /> || 1961\u201370<br />1972\u20132006<br /> || 2017<ref name=\"Inaugural\" />\n|-\n| 35 || [[John Henry Johnson]] || FB || 1960\u201365 || 2017<ref name=\"Inaugural\" />\n|-\n| 35 || [[Walt Kiesling]] || G<br />Coach<br /> || 1937\u201339<br />1939\u201344, 1954\u201356<br /> || 2017<ref name=\"Inaugural\" />\n|-\n| 58 || [[Jack Lambert (American football)|Jack Lambert]] || LB || 1974\u201384 || 2017<ref name=\"Inaugural\" />\n|-\n| 22 || [[Bobby Layne]] || QB || 1958\u201362 || 2017<ref name=\"Inaugural\" />\n|-\n| 15 || [[Johnny \"Blood\" McNally]] || FB<br />Coach<br /> || 1934, 1937\u201339<br />1937\u201339<br /> || 2017<ref name=\"Inaugural\" />\n|-\n| 81 || [[Elbie Nickel]] || TE || 1947\u201357 || 2019<ref name=\"Class of 2019\" />\n|-\n| \u2014 || [[Chuck Noll]] || Coach || 1969\u201391 || 2017<ref name=\"Inaugural\" />\n|-\n| \u2014 || [[Bill Nunn (American football)|Bill Nunn]] || Scout<br />Assistant Director Player Personnel<br />Senior Scout<br /> || 1968\u20132014 || 2018<ref name=\"Class of 2018\" />\n|-\n| \u2014 || [[Rooney family|Art Rooney, Jr.]] || Personnel Director<br />Vice President<br /> || 1965\u201386<br />1987\u2013present<br />|| 2018<ref name=\"Class of 2018\" />\n|-\n| \u2014 || [[Art Rooney, Sr.]] || Founder<br />President<br />Chairman of the Board<br /> || 1933\u201388 || 2017<ref name=\"Inaugural\" />\n|-\n| \u2014 || [[Dan Rooney|Dan Rooney, Sr.]] || President<br />Chairman<br /> || 1955\u20132017 || 2017<ref name=\"Inaugural\" />\n|-\n| 34 || [[Andy Russell (American football)|Andy Russell]] || LB || 1963, 1966\u201376 || 2017<ref name=\"Inaugural\" />\n|-\n| 31 || [[Donnie Shell]] || S || 1974\u201387 || 2017<ref name=\"Inaugural\" />\n|-\n| 82 || [[John Stallworth]] || WR || 1974\u201387 || 2017<ref name=\"Inaugural\" />\n|-\n| 70 || [[Ernie Stautner]] || DT || 1950\u201363 || 2017<ref name=\"Inaugural\" />\n|-\n| 88 || [[Lynn Swann]] || WR || 1974\u201382 || 2017<ref name=\"Inaugural\" />\n|-\n| 86 || [[Hines Ward]] || WR || 1998\u20132011 || 2019<ref name=\"Class of 2019\" />\n|-\n| 52 || [[Mike Webster]] || C || 1974\u201388 || 2017<ref name=\"Inaugural\" />\n|-\n| 26 || [[Rod Woodson]] || CB || 1987\u201396 || 2017<ref name=\"Inaugural\" />\n|}\n\n== Coaches ==\n{{Main|List of Pittsburgh Steelers head coaches}}\nThe Steelers have had 16 coaches through their history. They have cycled through the least amount of [[head coach]]es in the modern NFL history.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://deadspin.com/how-fast-has-your-nfl-team-cycled-through-coaches-1543761532|title=How Fast Has Your NFL Team Cycled Through Coaches?|last=Fischer-Baum|first=Reuben|work=Deadspin|access-date=July 28, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> Their first coach was [[Forrest Douds]], who coached them to a 3\u20136\u20132 record in [[1933 Pittsburgh Pirates (NFL) season|1933]]. [[Chuck Noll]] had the longest term as head coach with the Steelers; he is one of only four coaches to coach a single NFL team for 23 years.<ref name=\"History\" /> Hired prior to the [[2007 Pittsburgh Steelers season|2007 season]], the Steelers current coach is [[Mike Tomlin]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Dulac|first=Gerry|title=Tomlin, 34, is NFL's rising coaching star|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/07018/754788-66.stm|newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=January 18, 2007|accessdate=April 27, 2008}}</ref>\n\n=== Current staff ===\n{{Pittsburgh Steelers staff}}\n\n=== Offensive coordinator history ===\nSource:<ref name=\"AllTimeSteelersCoaches\">{{cite web|title=All-Time Assistant Coaches|url=http://prod.static.steelers.clubs.nfl.com/assets/docs/Pittsburgh-Steelers-Media-Guide.pdf#page=425|publisher=Pittsburgh Steelers|work=2017 Official Pittsburgh Steelers Media Guide|date=September 26, 2017|accessdate=May 18, 2018}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers|border=2}};\"|Years !! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers|border=2}};\"|Name\n|-\n| 2018\u2013present || [[Randy Fichtner]]\n|-\n| 2012\u20132017 || [[Todd Haley]]\n|-\n| 2007\u20132011 || [[Bruce Arians]]\n|-\n| 2004\u20132006 || [[Ken Whisenhunt]]\n|-\n| 2001\u20132003 || [[Mike Mularkey]]\n|-\n| 1999\u20132000 || [[Kevin Gilbride]]\n|-\n| 1998 || [[Ray Sherman]]\n|-\n| 1996\u20131997 || [[Chan Gailey]]\n|-\n| 1992\u20131995 || [[Ron Erhardt]]\n|-\n| 1990\u20131991 || [[Joe Walton]]\n|-\n| 1983\u20131989 || [[Tom Moore (American football coach)|Tom Moore]]\n|}\n\n=== Defensive coordinator history ===\nSource:<ref name=\"AllTimeSteelersCoaches\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers|border=2}};\"|Years !! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers|border=2}};\"|Name\n|-\n| 2015\u2013present || [[Keith Butler (American football)|Keith Butler]]\n|-\n| 2004\u20132014<br>1995\u20131996 || [[Dick LeBeau]]\n|-\n| 2000\u20132003 || [[Tim Lewis]]\n|-\n| 1997\u20131999 || [[Jim Haslett]]\n|-\n| 1992\u20131994 || [[Dom Capers]]\n|-\n| 1990\u20131991 || [[Dave Brazil (American football)|Dave Brazil]]\n|-\n| 1989 || [[Rod Rust]]\n|-\n| 1984\u20131988 || [[Tony Dungy]]\n|-\n| 1979\u20131983 || [[Woody Widenhofer]]\n|-\n| 1978 || [[George Perles]]\n|-\n| 1973\u20131977 || [[Bud Carson]]\n|}\n\n== Media ==\n[[File:Pittsburgh Steelers radio affiliates.png|thumb|right|Map of radio affiliates.]]\n{{Further|Pittsburgh Steelers Radio Network}}\nAs of 2006, the Steelers' [[Flagship (radio)|flagship radio stations]] were [[WDVE]] 102.5 FM and [[WBGG (AM)|WBGG]] 970 AM. Both stations are owned by [[iHeartMedia]]. Games are also available on 51 radio stations in [[Pennsylvania]], [[Western Maryland]], [[Ohio]], and Northern [[West Virginia]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Steelers Radio Network|url=https://www.steelers.com/news/radio-info.html|publisher=Pittsburgh Steelers|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180115234631/https://www.steelers.com/news/radio-info.html|archivedate=January 15, 2018|accessdate=May 18, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> The announcers are [[Bill Hillgrove]] and [[Tunch Ilkin]]. [[Craig Wolfley]] is the sideline reporter. [[Myron Cope]], the longtime [[color analyst]] and inventor of the \"[[Terrible Towel]]\", retired after the [[2004 NFL season|2004 season]], and died in 2008.\n\nPre-season games not shown on one of the national broadcasters are seen on [[CBS]] [[Owned-and-operated station|O&O]] [[KDKA-TV]], channel 2; [[The CW Television Network|sister CW O&O]] [[WPCW]], channel 19; and [[AT&T SportsNet Pittsburgh]]. KDKA-TV's [[Bob Pompeani]] and former Steelers quarterback [[Charlie Batch]] do the announcing for the pre-season games, as well as the two hosting the pre-game program ''Steelers Kickoff'' during the regular season prior to the national airing of ''[[The NFL Today]]''. Pompeani and former Steelers [[Lineman (American football)|lineman]] [[Chris Hoke]] also host the ''Xfinity Xtra Point'' following the game on days when [[CBS]] does not have that week's NFL doubleheader. When CBS has a week's doubleheader, the show airs on WPCW. Coach Mike Tomlin's weekly press conference is shown live on AT&T SportsNet Pittsburgh. Both Batch and Hoke replaced former Steelers lineman [[Edmund Nelson (American football)|Edmund Nelson]], who retired from broadcasting in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Former Steelers Charlie Batch and Chris Hoke join KDKA-TV broadcasts|url=http://www.steelers.com/news/article-1/Former-Steelers-Charlie-Batch-and-Chris-Hoke-join-KDKA-TV-broadcasts/4714b59b-0d6f-40b1-839d-6fd67c2c2a32|publisher=Pittsburgh Steelers|date=May 5, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150507210415/http://www.steelers.com/news/article-1/Former-Steelers-Charlie-Batch-and-Chris-Hoke-join-KDKA-TV-broadcasts/4714b59b-0d6f-40b1-839d-6fd67c2c2a32|archivedate=May 7, 2015|accessdate=May 18, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n''[[Thursday Night Football]]'' broadcasts are shown locally on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] affiliate [[WPGH-TV]], channel 53 (along with home games with NFC opponents and some flexed interconference games), while ''[[ESPN Monday Night Football]]'' broadcasts are shown locally on [[WTAE-TV]], channel 4. (WTAE-TV is owned by the [[Hearst Corporation]], which owns a 20% stake in ESPN.) By virtue of being members of the AFC, most of the Steelers' games air on CBS and KDKA. ''[[NBC Sunday Night Football]]'' games are carried by [[WPXI]], channel 11, in the market.\n\nThe Steelers hold a national contract with [[Grupo Imagen]] for radio rights to their games in Mexico; Imagen broadcasts the Steelers on their stations in 17 Mexican cities.\n\n=== Figures with broadcasting r\u00e9sum\u00e9s ===\n{{Main|List of Pittsburgh Steelers figures in broadcasting}}\n\nThe Steelers franchise has a rich history of producing well-known sportscasters over the years. The most famous of these is probably [[Myron Cope]], who served as a Steelers radio [[color commentator]] for 35 seasons ({{Steelers season|1970}}\u2013{{Steelers season|2004}}).\n\nSeveral former Steelers players have gone on to careers in media after completing their playing careers.\n\n=== Newspaper ===\nThe ''Steelers Digest'' is the only official newspaper for the Pittsburgh Steelers. It has been published for 22 years and is currently published by Dolphin/Curtis Publishing in Miami, Florida, which also handles several other publications. The newspaper is very widely acknowledged by Steelers fans. Issues are mailed out to paying subscribers weekly through the season after every regular season game and continues through playoffs as long as the Steelers do. After a Super Bowl victory, a bonus issue is published, which is followed by a draft preview, draft recap, and training camp edition every other month, then leading into the pre-season. There are typically 24 issues of the paper within a publishing year. The newspaper is listed on the official Steelers.com page.\n\n=== Usage in popular culture ===\nThe Steelers success over several decades has permeated film and literature.  The Steelers are portrayed in the following big-budget Hollywood films:\n*The January 11, 1975 episode of the ''[[Mary Tyler Moore Show]]'' used the team's first Super Bowl as the plot device.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n*''[[Black Sunday (1977 film)|Black Sunday]]'' in 1977\n*''[[Heaven Can Wait (1978 film)|Heaven Can Wait]]'' in 1978\n*''[[Smokey and the Bandit II]]'' in 1980\n*''[[Fighting Back: The Rocky Bleier Story|Fighting Back]]'' in 1980\n*''[[Hey Kid, Catch!]]'' in 1980\n*''[[...All the Marbles]]'' in 1981\n*''[[Evening Shade]]'' (TV series) 1990\u20131994\n*''[[The Waterboy]]'' cameo by [[Bill Cowher]] in 1998\n*''[[The Longest Yard (2005 film)|The Longest Yard]]'' in 2005\n*''[[The Chief (play)|The Chief]]'' a theater production.\n*''[[Black and Yellow]]'' in 2010.\n*''[[The Dark Knight Rises]]'' in 2012 features several Steelers players as the fictional Gotham Rogues, which was filmed in Heinz Field\n*''[[Mad Men (season 6)|Mad Men's]]'' April 14, 2013 episode has [[Don Draper]], [[Pete Campbell]] and [[Roger Sterling]] meeting with two [[H.J. Heinz Company|HJ Heinz]] executives. The executives are told that not only would the ad firm have given them tickets to the Steelers' November 19, 1967 game at the Giants, the firm would have worked it so that the Steelers would have won (they lost 20\u201328).\n*''[[Concussion (2015 film)|Concussion]]'' in 2015 features players from the team suffering from [[Chronic traumatic encephalopathy|CTE]].\n\nThe protagonist of [[John Grisham]]'s novel \"[[The Associate (novel)|The Associate]]\" is a staunch Steelers fan.\n\nIn the summer of 2019, the [[Kennywood]] theme park located near Pittsburgh, opened a new land themed to the Pittsburgh Steelers, [[Kennywood#Themed areas|Steelers Country]], featuring a major record-breaking coaster, the [[Steel Curtain (roller coaster)|Steel Curtain]]. The land, in addition to this ride, features a Steelers-themed experience, and an 'End Zone Restaurant'.\n\n== The Chuck Noll Foundation for Brain Injury Research ==\nThe Steelers helped launch the Chuck Noll Foundation for Brain Injury Research in November 2016 by donating $1 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/sports/steelers/2016/11/17/Steelers-help-launch-Chuck-Noll-Foundation-for-Brain-Injury-Research-with-1-million-contribution/stories/201611170190|title=Steelers help launch Chuck Noll Foundation for Brain Injury Research with $1 million contribution|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|access-date=June 14, 2017|language=en}}</ref>  The Foundation, started by Steelers president Art Rooney II, focuses on education and research regarding brain injuries and sports-related concussions.\n\nIn June 2017, the Steelers announced an inaugural charity walk to raise money for the foundation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Steelers announce inaugural charity walk|url=http://www.steelers.com/news/article-1/Steelers-announce-inaugural-charity-walk-/2a404a2b-fdba-4075-9233-2ca3d62ce2d3|publisher=Pittsburgh Steelers|date=June 14, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170617175653/http://www.steelers.com/news/article-1/Steelers-announce-inaugural-charity-walk-/2a404a2b-fdba-4075-9233-2ca3d62ce2d3|archivedate=June 17, 2017|accessdate=May 18, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Pittsburgh Pro Football Hall of Fame]]\n* [[Active NFL playoff appearance streaks]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Pittsburgh Steelers}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.nfl.com/teams/pittsburghsteelers/profile?team=PIT Pittsburgh Steelers] at the [[National Football League]] official website\n\n{{Pittsburgh Steelers}}\n{{Navboxes\n|titlestyle = {{NFLPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers|border=2}}\n|list =\n{{NFL}}\n{{Pittsburgh sports}}\n{{Pennsylvania Sports}}\n}}\n{{Portal bar|American football|Pennsylvania}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Steelers|*]]\n[[Category:National Football League teams]]\n[[Category:Steagles]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs established in 1933]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Steelers}}\n{{pp-semi-indef}}\n{{short description|National Football League franchise in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL team\n| name = Pittsburgh Steelers\n| current = 2019 Pittsburgh Steelers season\n| wordmark = Pittsburgh Steelers Script.svg\n| logo = Pittsburgh Steelers logo.svg\n| founded = {{Start date and age|July 8, 1933}}<ref>{{cite web|title=A Tradition of Excellence|url=http://www.steelers.com/history/tradition-of-excellence.html|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC|website=Steelers.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100218100804/https://www.steelers.com/history/tradition-of-excellence.html|archivedate=February 18, 2010|accessdate=May 18, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| first_season = [[1933 Pittsburgh Pirates (NFL) season|1933]]\n| city = [[Heinz Field]]<br />[[Pittsburgh|Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]]\n| misc = '''Headquartered''' in [[UPMC Sports Performance Complex]]<br />Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania<br />'''Training camp''' in<br />[[Latrobe, Pennsylvania]]\n| uniform = File:Pittsb steelers uniforms17.png\n| colors = Black, gold<ref>{{cite news|last=Varley|first=Teresa|title=Color Rush, Throwback jersey dates revealed|url=https://www.steelers.com/news/color-rush-throwback-jersey-dates-revealed|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC|website=Steelers.com|date=July 30, 2019|access-date=September 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Pittsburgh Steelers Team Capsule|url=https://www.nfl.com/static/content/public/photo/2018/08/09/0ap3000000946101.pdf#page=124|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC|work=2018 Official National Football League Record and Fact Book|date=August 9, 2018|access-date=November 21, 2018}}</ref><br />{{color box|#000000}} {{color box|#FFB612}}\n| coach = [[Mike Tomlin]]\n| owner = [[Rooney family]]\n| chairman =\n| president = [[Art Rooney II]]\n| general manager = [[Kevin Colbert]]\n| mascot = [[#Mascot|Steely McBeam]]\n| hist_yr = 1940\u20131942; 1945\n| hist_misc =\n* Pittsburgh Pirates (1933\u20131939)\n| hist_misc2 =\n* [[Philadelphia Eagles|Phil]]-Pitt \"[[Steagles]]\" (1943)\n* [[Card-Pitt]] (1944)\n| nicknames =\n* [[Steel Curtain]] (Defensive line, 1969\u20131981)\n* Black and Gold Brigade\n| NFL_start_yr = 1933\n| division_hist =\n* Eastern Division (1933\u20131943, 1945\u20131949)\n* Western Division (1944)\n* American Conference (1950\u20131952)\n* Eastern Conference (1953\u20131969)\n** [[NFL Century Division|Century Division]] (1967\u20131969)\n* '''[[American Football Conference]] (1970\u2013present)'''\n** [[AFC Central]] (1970\u20132001)\n** '''[[AFC North]] (2002\u2013present)'''\n| no_league_champs = 6\n| no_sb_champs = 6\n| no_conf_champs = 8\n| no_div_champs = 23\n| sb_champs = {{NFL playoff year|1974}} ([[Super Bowl IX|IX]]), {{NFL playoff year|1975}} ([[Super Bowl X|X]]), {{NFL playoff year|1978}} ([[Super Bowl XIII|XIII]]), {{NFL playoff year|1979}} ([[Super Bowl XIV|XIV]]), {{NFL playoff year|2005}} ([[Super Bowl XL|XL]]), {{NFL playoff year|2008}} ([[Super Bowl XLIII|XLIII]])\n| conf_champs =\n* '''[[AFC Championship Game|AFC]]:''' [[Super Bowl IX|1974]], [[Super Bowl X|1975]], [[Super Bowl XIII|1978]], [[Super Bowl XIV|1979]], [[Super Bowl XXX|1995]], [[Super Bowl XL|2005]], [[Super Bowl XLIII|2008]], [[Super Bowl XLV|2010]]\n| div_champs =\n* '''[[AFC Central]]:''' {{NFL playoff year|1972}}, {{NFL playoff year|1974}}, {{NFL playoff year|1975}}, {{NFL playoff year|1976}}, {{NFL playoff year|1977}}, {{NFL playoff year|1978}}, {{NFL playoff year|1979}}, {{NFL playoff year|1983}}, {{NFL playoff year|1984}}, {{NFL playoff year|1992}}, {{NFL playoff year|1994}}, {{NFL playoff year|1995}}, {{NFL playoff year|1996}}, {{NFL playoff year|1997}}, {{NFL playoff year|2001}}\n* '''[[AFC North]]:''' {{NFL playoff year|2002}}, {{NFL playoff year|2004}}, {{NFL playoff year|2007}}, {{NFL playoff year|2008}}, {{NFL playoff year|2010}}, {{NFL playoff year|2014}}, {{NFL playoff year|2016}}, {{NFL playoff year|2017}}\n| playoff_appearances =\n* '''NFL:''' {{NFL playoff year|1947}}, {{NFL playoff year|1972}}, {{NFL playoff year|1973}}, {{NFL playoff year|1974}}, {{NFL playoff year|1975}}, {{NFL playoff year|1976}}, {{NFL playoff year|1977}}, {{NFL playoff year|1978}}, {{NFL playoff year|1979}}, {{NFL playoff year|1982}}, {{NFL playoff year|1983}}, {{NFL playoff year|1984}}, {{NFL playoff year|1989}}, {{NFL playoff year|1992}}, {{NFL playoff year|1993}}, {{NFL playoff year|1994}}, {{NFL playoff year|1995}}, {{NFL playoff year|1996}}, {{NFL playoff year|1997}}, {{NFL playoff year|2001}}, {{NFL playoff year|2002}}, {{NFL playoff year|2004}}, {{NFL playoff year|2005}}, {{NFL playoff year|2007}}, {{NFL playoff year|2008}}, {{NFL playoff year|2010}}, {{NFL playoff year|2011}}, {{NFL playoff year|2014}}, {{NFL playoff year|2015}}, {{NFL playoff year|2016}}, {{NFL playoff year|2017}}\n| no_playoff_appearances = 31\n| stadium_years =\n* [[Forbes Field]] (1933\u20131963)\n* [[Shibe Park]] (1943)\n* [[Comiskey Park]] (1944)\n* [[Pitt Stadium]] (1958\u20131969)\n* [[Three Rivers Stadium]] (1970\u20132000)\n* '''[[Heinz Field]] (2001\u2013present)'''\n| team_owners = '''[[Rooney family]] (1933\u2013present)'''\n| team_presidents =\n* [[Art Rooney]] (1933\u20131975)\n* [[Dan Rooney]] (1975\u20132002)\n* '''[[Art Rooney II]] (2002\u2013present)'''\n}}\n\nThe '''Pittsburgh Steelers''' are a professional [[American football]] team based in [[Pittsburgh]]. They compete in the [[National Football League]] (NFL) as a member club of the [[American Football Conference]] (AFC) [[AFC North|North]] division. Founded in {{Steelers season|1933}}, the Steelers are the seventh-oldest franchise in the NFL, and they are the oldest franchise in the AFC.<ref name=\"History\">{{cite web|title=Pittsburgh Steelers Team History|url=https://www.profootballhof.com/teams/pittsburgh-steelers/team-history/|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC|website=ProFootballHOF.com|access-date=January 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn contrast with their status as perennial also-rans in the pre-[[AFL\u2013NFL merger|merger]] NFL, where they were the oldest team never to have won a league championship, the Steelers of the post-[[AFL\u2013NFL merger|merger]] (modern) era are among the most successful NFL franchises. The team is tied with the [[New England Patriots]] for the most [[Super Bowl]] titles at six, and they have both played in (16 times) and hosted (11 times) more conference championship games than any other team in the NFL. The Steelers have also won eight [[AFC Championship Game|AFC championships]], tied with the [[Denver Broncos]], but behind the Patriots' record 11 AFC championships. The team is tied with the Broncos and [[Dallas Cowboys]] for the second-most Super Bowl appearances with eight. They lost their most recent championship appearance, [[Super Bowl XLV]], on February 6, 2011.\n\nThe Steelers, whose history may be traced to a [[J.P. Rooneys|regional pro team that was established in the early 1920s]], joined the NFL as the '''Pittsburgh Pirates''' on July 8, 1933. The team was owned by [[Art Rooney]] and took its original name from the [[Pittsburgh Pirates|baseball team of the same name]], as was common practice for NFL teams at the time.<ref name=\"History\" /> To distinguish them from the baseball team, local media took to calling the football team the '''Rooneymen''', an unofficial nickname that persisted for decades after the team had adopted its current nickname. The ownership of the Steelers has remained within the Rooney family since the organization's founding.<ref>{{cite web|author=ESPN.com |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/print?id=2897545&type=story |title=ESPN.com&nbsp;\u2013 The Best: Owner |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=June 8, 2007 |accessdate=September 3, 2012}}</ref> Art Rooney's son, [[Dan Rooney]], owned the team from 1988 until his death in 2017. Much control of the franchise has been given to Dan Rooney's son, [[Art Rooney II]].\n\nThe Steelers enjoy a large, widespread [[Pittsburgh Steelers#Fanbase|fanbase]] nicknamed [[Steeler Nation]].<ref name=\"Mosley\">{{cite news |first= Matt|last= Mosley|title= NFL's best fans? We gotta hand it to Steelers (barely)|url= http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/preview08/columns/story?id=3530077|publisher=ESPN |date= August 29, 2008|accessdate=August 30, 2008}}</ref> They currently play their home games at [[Heinz Field]] on Pittsburgh's [[North Side (Pittsburgh)|North Side]] in the [[North Shore (Pittsburgh)|North Shore]] neighborhood, which also hosts the [[University of Pittsburgh]] [[Pittsburgh Panthers football|Panthers]]. Built in 2001, the stadium replaced [[Three Rivers Stadium]], which had hosted the Steelers for 31 seasons. Prior to Three Rivers, the Steelers had played their games in [[Pitt Stadium]] and at [[Forbes Field]].\n\n== Franchise history ==\n<!--NOTE:This is a basic summary of the Steelers' history. If you wish to add information, please visit the History of the Pittsburgh Steelers article.-->{{details|History of the Pittsburgh Steelers}}\n{{See also|American football in Western Pennsylvania}}\n\nThe Pittsburgh Steelers of the NFL first took to the field as the [[1933 Pittsburgh Pirates (NFL) season|Pittsburgh Pirates]] on September 20, 1933, losing 23\u20132 to the [[1933 New York Giants season|New York Giants]].<ref name=\"History\" /> Through the 1930s, the Pirates never finished higher than second place in their division, or with a record better than .500 ({{Steelers season|1936}}).<ref>{{cite web|title=Past Standings|url=http://static.nfl.com/static/content/public/image/history/pdfs/History/2013/373_399_Past_Standings.pdf|publisher=NFL Enterprises LLC|work=2013 Official National Football League Record and Fact Book|date=September 25, 2013|accessdate=May 18, 2018}}</ref> Pittsburgh did make history in {{Steelers season|1938}} by signing [[Byron White]], a future [[Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States|Justice]] of the [[U.S. Supreme Court]], to what was at the time the biggest contract in NFL history, but he played only one year with the Pirates before signing with the [[Detroit Lions]].<ref name=\"History\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Byron White|url=https://www.ca10.uscourts.gov/education/byron-white|publisher=United States Court of Appeals for the Tenth Circuit|accessdate=May 18, 2018}}</ref> Prior to the 1940 season, the Pirates renamed themselves the Steelers.\n\nDuring World War II, the Steelers experienced player shortages. They twice merged with other NFL franchises to field a team. During the [[1943 NFL season|1943 season]], they merged with the [[Philadelphia Eagles]] forming the \"Phil-Pitt Eagles\" and were known as the \"[[Steagles]]\". This team went 5\u20134\u20131. In [[1944 NFL season|1944]], they merged with the [[Chicago Cardinals (NFL, 1920\u201359)|Chicago Cardinals]] and were known as Card-Pitt (or, mockingly, as the \"Carpets\").<ref name=\"History\" /> This team finished 0\u201310, marking the only winless team in franchise history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/s_150100.html|title=World War II Steagles to be honored at tonight's game&nbsp;\u2013 Pittsburgh Tribune-Review<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090330174652/http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/s_150100.html|archivedate=March 30, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe [[1947 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Steelers]] made the playoffs for the first time in {{NFL Year|1947}}, tying for first place in the division at 8\u20134 with the [[1947 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]]. This forced a [[1947 NFL playoffs|tie-breaking playoff game]] at [[Forbes Field]], which the Steelers lost 21\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/pitindex.htm|title=Pittsburgh Steelers Team Encyclopedia \u2013 Pro-Football-Reference.com|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com}}</ref> That would be Pittsburgh's only playoff game in the pre-merger era; they did qualify for a \"[[Playoff Bowl]]\" in 1962 as the second-best team in their conference, but this was not considered an official playoff.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmbolding.com/BSR/The_Playoff_Bowl.htm|title=Unconfigured Site|website=www.mmbolding.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070415053025/http://www.mmbolding.com/BSR/The_Playoff_Bowl.htm|archivedate=April 15, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn {{Steelers season|1970}}, the year they moved into [[Three Rivers Stadium]] and the year of the [[AFL\u2013NFL merger]], the Pittsburgh Steelers were one of three old-guard NFL teams to switch to the newly formed [[American Football Conference]] (the others being the [[Cleveland Browns]] and the [[Baltimore Colts]]), in order to equalize the number of teams in the two conferences of the newly merged league. The Steelers also received a $3 million (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|3|1970|r=1}}}} million today) relocation fee, which was a windfall for them; for years they rarely had enough to build a true contending team.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sports/super-bowl/the-game/20110201-sherrington-dallas-meeting-in-66-saved-steelers-from-stinking.ece | title=Dallas meeting in '66 saved Steelers from stinking | first=Kevin | last=Sherrington | work=Dallas Morning News | date=February 1, 2011 | accessdate=February 6, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== The Chuck Noll era ===\n{{details|Chuck Noll}}\n[[File:1983 Steelers Police - 04 Terry Bradshaw (crop).jpg|thumb|175px|[[Pro Football Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame]] quarterback Terry Bradshaw led the Steelers to four Super Bowl titles during the 1970s.]]\nThe Steelers' history of bad luck changed with the hiring of coach [[Chuck Noll]] from the NFL champion Baltimore Colts for the [[1969 NFL season|1969 season]]. Noll's most remarkable talent was in his draft selections, taking Hall of Famers [[Joe Greene (American football)|\"Mean\" Joe Greene]] in [[1969 NFL Draft|1969]], [[Terry Bradshaw]] and [[Mel Blount]] in [[1970 NFL Draft|1970]], [[Jack Ham]] in [[1971 NFL Draft|1971]], [[Franco Harris]] in [[1972 NFL Draft|1972]],<ref>[http://www.databasefootball.com/draft/draftteam.htm?tm=PIT&lg=NFL Pittsburgh Steelers Draft History, Stats and more on databaseFootball.com<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070203142335/http://www.databasefootball.com/draft/draftteam.htm?tm=PIT&lg=nfl |date=February 3, 2007 }}</ref> and finally, in 1974, pulling off the incredible feat of selecting four Hall of Famers in one draft year, [[Lynn Swann]], [[Jack Lambert (American football)|Jack Lambert]], [[John Stallworth]], and [[Mike Webster]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.profootballhof.com/history/general/draft/1974.jsp|title=Timeline Detail \u2013 Pro Football Hall of Fame Official Site|website=www.profootballhof.com}}</ref> The Pittsburgh Steelers' [[1974 NFL Draft|1974 draft]] was their best ever; no other team has ever drafted four future Hall of Famers in one year, and only very few (including the 1970 Steelers) have drafted two or more in one year.\n\nThe players drafted in the early 1970s formed the base of an NFL dynasty, making the playoffs in eight seasons and becoming the only team in NFL history to win four [[Super Bowl]]s in six years, as well as the first to win more than two.  They also enjoyed a regular season streak of 49 consecutive wins ({{Steelers season|1971}}\u2013{{Steelers season|1979}}) against teams that would finish with a losing record that year.\n\nThe [[1980 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Steelers]] suffered a rash of injuries in the [[1980 NFL season|1980 season]] and missed the playoffs with a 9\u20137 record. The [[1981 NFL season|1981 season]] was no better, with an 8\u20138 showing. The team was then hit with the retirements of all their key players from the Super Bowl years. \"Mean\" Joe Greene retired after the [[1981 NFL season|1981 season]], Lynn Swann and Jack Ham after [[1982 NFL season|1982]]'s playoff berth, Terry Bradshaw and Mel Blount after [[1983 NFL season|1983]]'s divisional championship, and Jack Lambert after [[1984 NFL season|1984]]'s AFC Championship Game appearance.\n\nAfter those retirements, the franchise skidded to its first losing seasons since 1971. Though still competitive, the Steelers would not finish above .500 in [[1985 NFL season|1985]], [[1986 NFL season|1986]], and [[1988 NFL season|1988]]. In [[1987 NFL season|1987]], the year of the [[1987 NFL strike|players' strike]], the [[1987 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Steelers]] finished with a record of 8\u20137, but missed the playoffs. In [[1989 NFL season|1989]], they would reach the second round of the playoffs on the strength of [[Merrill Hoge]] and [[Rod Woodson]] before narrowly missing the playoffs in each of the next two seasons, Noll's last seasons.\n\nNoll's career record with Pittsburgh was 209\u2013156\u20131.\n\n=== The Bill Cowher era ===\n{{details|Bill Cowher}}\nIn 1992, [[Chuck Noll]] retired and was succeeded by [[Kansas City Chiefs]] defensive coordinator [[Bill Cowher]], a native of the Pittsburgh suburb of [[Crafton, Pennsylvania|Crafton]].\n\n[[File:Pittsburgh Steelers five rings.jpg|left|thumb|200px|Steelers' five Super Bowl rings before 2009]]\nCowher led the Steelers to the playoffs in each of his first six seasons, a feat that had been accomplished only by legendary coach [[Paul Brown]] of the [[Cleveland Browns]]. In those first six seasons, Cowher coached them as deep as the [[AFC Championship Game]] three times and following the [[1995 NFL season|1995 season]] an appearance in [[Super Bowl XXX]] on the strength of the \"Blitzburgh\" defense. However, the Steelers lost to the [[1995 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]] in Super Bowl XXX, two weeks after a thrilling [[1995 AFC Championship game|AFC Championship]] victory over the [[1995 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]]. Cowher produced the franchise's record-tying fifth Super Bowl win in [[Super Bowl XL]] over the [[National Football Conference|NFC]] champion [[2005 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]] ten years later. With that victory, the Steelers became the third team to win five Super Bowls, and the first sixth-seeded playoff team to reach and win the Super Bowl since the NFL expanded to a 12-team post-season tournament in 1990.  He coached through the 2006 season which ended with an 8\u20138 record, just short of the playoffs.  Overall Cowher's teams reached the playoffs 10 of 15 seasons with six AFC Championship Games, two Super Bowl berths and a championship.\n\nCowher's career record with Pittsburgh was 149\u201390\u20131 in the regular season and 161\u201399\u20131 overall, including playoff games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/coaches/CowhBi0.htm |title=Bill Cowher Record, Statistics, and Category Ranks |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== The Mike Tomlin era ===\n{{details|Mike Tomlin}}\n[[File:Ben Roethlisberger throwback.jpg|thumb|Roethlisberger in a Steelers' throwback jersey during the team's 500th win in franchise history]]\n\nOn January 7, 2007, Cowher resigned from coaching the Steelers, citing a need to spend more time with his family. He did not use the term \"retire\", leaving open a possible return to the NFL as coach of another team. A three-man committee consisting of Art Rooney II, Dan Rooney, and Kevin Colbert was set up to conduct interviews for the head coaching vacancy.<ref>{{cite news|last=Labriola|first=Bob|title=The search has begun|url=http://news.steelers.com/article/73452/|publisher=Pittsburgh Steelers|date=January 5, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070111192421/http://news.steelers.com/article/73452/|archivedate=January 11, 2007|accessdate=May 18, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> The candidates interviewed included: offensive coordinator [[Ken Whisenhunt]], offensive line coach [[Russ Grimm]], former offensive coordinator [[Chan Gailey]], [[Minnesota Vikings]] defensive coordinator [[Mike Tomlin]], and [[Chicago Bears]] defensive coordinator [[Ron Rivera]]. On January 22, 2007, [[Mike Tomlin]] was announced as Cowher's successor as head coach. Tomlin is the first African-American to be named head coach of the Pittsburgh Steelers in its 75-year history. Tomlin became the third consecutive Steelers Head Coach to go to the Super Bowl, equaling the Dallas Cowboys (Tom Landry, Jimmy Johnson and Barry Switzer) in this achievement. He was named the Motorola 2008 Coach of the Year. On February 1, 2009, Tomlin led the Steelers to their second Super Bowl of this decade, and went on to win 27\u201323 against the [[2008 Arizona Cardinals season|Arizona Cardinals]]. At age 36, he was the youngest head coach to ever win the Super Bowl, and he is only the second African-American coach to ever win the Super Bowl ([[Tony Dungy]] was the first). The 2010 season made Tomlin the only coach to reach the Super Bowl twice before the age of 40.  Tomlin led the team to his second Super Bowl ([[Super Bowl XLV]]) on February 6, 2011. However, the Steelers were defeated in their eighth Super Bowl appearance by the Green Bay Packers by the score of 31\u201325. The Steelers recorded their 400th victory in 2012 after defeating the [[Washington Redskins]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pittsburgh.cbslocal.com/2012/10/29/steelers-400th-win-in-the-nfl-comes-against-the-redskins/|title=Steelers' 400th Win In The NFL Comes Against The Redskins|publisher=CBS Local|date=October 29, 2012|accessdate=October 29, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThrough the 2016 season, Tomlin's record is 111\u201363, including playoffs. He is the first Pittsburgh coach without a losing season. The 2013\u20132017 seasons were noted for record performances from the \"Killer B's\". This trio consisted of [[Antonio Brown]], [[Ben Roethlisberger]] and [[Le'Veon Bell]]. Occasionally, the \"Killer B's\" has also included kicker [[Chris Boswell]] due to his ability to hit game-winning field goals.\n\n=== Summary ===\nSince the NFL merger in 1970, the Pittsburgh Steelers have compiled a regular season record of 444\u2013282\u20132 (.635) and an overall record of 480-305-2 (.635) including the playoffs<!--as of February 7, 2017.-->, reached the playoffs 30 times, won their division 22 times, played in 16 AFC championship games, and won six of eight Super Bowls. They are also the only NFL team not to have a season with 12 or more losses since the league expanded to a 16-game schedule in 1978.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/nfl/recap?gameId=310102007 |title=San Diego Chargers vs. Denver Broncos&nbsp;\u2013 Recap&nbsp;\u2013 January 02, 2011&nbsp;\u2013 ESPN |publisher=Scores.espn.go.com |date=January 2, 2011 |accessdate=September 3, 2012}}</ref><!--NOTE: This is a basic summary of the Steelers' history. If you wish to add more information, please visit the History of the Pittsburgh Steelers article.-->\n\n=== Ownership ===\n[[File:Heinz Field 2010.JPG|thumb|Heinz Field, current home of the Pittsburgh Steelers.]]\n\nSince 2008, the [[Rooney family]] has brought in several investors for the team while retaining control of the team itself. This came about so that the team could comply with NFL ownership regulations.<ref>{{cite news|title=Steelers Ownership Transition|url=http://news.steelers.com/article/91693/|publisher=Pittsburgh Steelers|date=July 7, 2008|accessdate=July 13, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080713092629/http://news.steelers.com/article/91693/|archivedate=July 13, 2008|df= mdy-all}}</ref> [[Dan Rooney]], and his son, [[Art Rooney II]], president of the franchise, wanted to stay involved with the franchise, while two of the brothers&nbsp;\u2013 Timothy and Patrick&nbsp;\u2013 wanted to further pursue [[Horse racing|racetracks]] that they own in Florida and New York.<ref>{{cite news|title= Rooneys look to restructure Steelers ownership|url= http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08189/895371-66.stm|work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|date= July 7, 2008|accessdate=July 13, 2008}}</ref> Since 2006, many of the racetracks have added [[Slot machine|video slot machines]], causing them to violate \"NFL policy that prohibits involvement with racetrack and gambling interests\".<ref>{{cite news |first= Gerry|last= Dulac|title= Steelers ownership in turmoil|url= http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08190/895506-66.stm|work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|date= July 8, 2008|accessdate=July 13, 2008}}</ref>\n\nUpon Dan Rooney's death in 2017, he and Art Rooney II retained control of the team with the league-minimum 30%, the following make up the other investors:\n*The Robert A. Paul family of Pittsburgh and Los Angeles, which is primarily involved with Pittsburgh-based [[Ampco Pittsburgh]] Corporation as well as Morton's Restaurant Group, Urban Active Fitness, Meyer Products and Harley Marine Services.  Additionally, family members serve on numerous [[board of directors|boards]], including Cornell University, [[University of Pittsburgh Medical Center|UPMC]], [[University of Pittsburgh]], the [[American Red Cross]], [[Harvard Medical School]] and the [[Loomis Chaffee]] School.<ref name=\"Haslam\" />\n*Former Steelers [[wide receiver]] [[John Stallworth]], a member of the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]].<ref name=\"Stallworth\">{{cite news|last=Bouchette|first=Ed|title=Stallworth now a Steelers owner|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/sports/2009/03/24/Stallworth-now-a-Steelers-owner/stories/200903240126|newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=March 24, 2009|accessdate=May 18, 2018}}</ref>\n*Several other members of the Rooney family, including Art Rooney Jr., John Rooney, and the McGinley family, who are cousins to the Rooneys.\n*[[Legendary Pictures]] president and CEO Thomas Tull.<ref name=\"Haslam\">{{cite news|title=NFL owners approve altered Steelers ownership|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=3776644|publisher=ESPN|date=December 17, 2008|accessdate=May 18, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[GTCR]] chairman [[Bruce Rauner|Bruce V. Rauner]].<ref name=\"Stallworth\" /> [[File:Pittsburgh Steelers at the White House 2009-05-21 2.JPG|thumb|210px|President Obama poses with the Steelers in 2009. Left to right: [[Ben Roethlisberger]], [[Hines Ward]], Obama, and [[Dan Rooney]].]]\n*The Peter Varischetti family of [[Brockway, Pennsylvania|Brockway]], which owns several [[nursing home]]s and a [[Commercial property|commercial real estate]] business.<ref name=\"Stallworth\" />\n*Paul Evanson, chairman, president, and CEO of [[Allegheny Energy]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Steelers Add Partner To Ownership Group|url=http://www.steelers.com/news/article-1/Steelers-Add-Partner-To-Ownership-Group/E42AFD5C-BBE9-433D-9802-57CFE2B450E2|publisher=Pittsburgh Steelers|date=December 22, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613171722/http://www.steelers.com/news/article-1/Steelers-Add-Partner-To-Ownership-Group/E42AFD5C-BBE9-433D-9802-57CFE2B450E2|archivedate=June 13, 2011|accessdate=May 18, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*Russ and Scott Swank of [[Lower Burrell, Pennsylvania|Lower Burrell]].<ref name=\"Swank\">[http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/sports/steelers/browns-owner-haslam-sells-stock-in-steelers-683091/ Browns owner Haslam sells stock in Steelers&nbsp;\u2013 Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]. Post-gazette.com (April 11, 2013). Retrieved on 2013-07-23.</ref>\n\n=== Season-by-season records ===\n{{details|List of Pittsburgh Steelers seasons}}\n\nThrough the end of the [[2015 Pittsburgh Steelers season|2015]] season, the Steelers have an all-time record of 624\u2013552\u201321, including playoffs. In recent seasons the Steelers have generally performed well, qualifying for the playoffs six times in the past ten seasons and winning the Super Bowl twice since {{Steelers season|2005}}.<ref name=\"FranchiseEncyclopedia\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/pit/|title=Pittsburgh Steelers Franchise Encyclopedia|publisher=[[Pro Football Reference]]|accessdate=April 8, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn the NFL's \"modern era\" (since the AFL\u2013NFL merger in 1970) the Steelers have posted the best record in the league.  The franchise has won the most regular season games, the most playoff games (33 playoff wins; the Dallas Cowboys are second with 32), won the most divisional titles (20), has played in the most conference championship games\n(15), hosted the most conference championship games (11), and is tied with the Dallas Cowboys, the Denver Broncos and the New England Patriots for the most Super Bowl appearances (8). The Steelers have the best winning percentage (including every expansion team), earned the most All-Pro nominations, and have accumulated the most Super Bowl wins (6) since the modern game started in 1970. Since the merger, the team's playoff record is 33\u201319 (.635), which is second best in terms of playoff winning percentage behind the [[Green Bay Packers]]' playoff record of 28\u201316 (.636), through January 23, 2011. {{citation needed|date=April 2010}}\n\n=== Civil rights advocacy ===\nThe franchise, along with the Rooney family have for generations been strong advocates for equality of opportunity for both minorities and women.  Among these achievements of the Steelers was the first to hire an African-American assistant coach (September 29, 1957 with [[Lowell Perry]]), the first to start an African-American quarterback (December 3, 1973 with [[Joe Gilliam]]), the first team to boast of an African-American Super Bowl MVP (January 12, 1975 with [[Franco Harris]]), the first to hire an African-American Coordinator (September 2, 1984 with [[Tony Dungy]]), the first owner to push for passage of an \"equal opportunity\" mandating that at least one minority candidate is given an interview in all head coach hiring decisions throughout the league (the Rooney Rule in the early 2000s), and the first to hire a female as full-time athletic trainer ([[Ariko Iso]] on July 24, 2002).<br />{{small|Note: Although [[Marlin Briscoe]] is sometimes erroneously cited as the first African-American starting quarterback in 1968, this was not for an NFL team and not in an NFL game (the Denver Broncos, for which Briscoe played, were an American Football League team then), additionally the vast majority of Briscoe's career was not as quarterback.}}\n\n== Logo and uniforms ==\n<!--NOTE:This is a basic summary of the Steelers' logo and uniforms. If you wish to add information, please visit the Logos and uniforms of the Pittsburgh Steelers article.-->{{details|Logos and uniforms of the Pittsburgh Steelers}}\n[[File:US Airways Steelers.jpg|thumb|US Airways logo jet featuring the colors of the Pittsburgh Steelers]]\n[[File:Pittsburgh Steelers Script.svg|right|thumb|150px|The script logo.]]The Steelers have used black and gold as their colors since the club's inception, the lone exception being the 1943 season when they merged with the [[Philadelphia Eagles]] and formed the \"[[Steagles]]\"; the team's colors at that time were green and white as a result of wearing Eagles uniforms. Originally, the team wore solid gold-colored helmets and black jerseys. The Steelers' black and gold colors are now shared by all major professional teams in the city, including the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] in baseball and the [[Pittsburgh Penguins]] in ice hockey, and also the [[Pittsburgh Power]] of the re-formed [[Arena Football League]], and the [[Pittsburgh Passion]] of the [[Independent Women's Football League]]. The shade of gold differs slightly among teams: the Penguins have previously used \"Vegas Gold\", a color similar to metallic gold, and the Pirates' gold is a darker mustard yellow-gold, while the Steelers \"gold\" is more of a bright canary yellow.  Black and gold are also the colors of the [[Flag of Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|city's official flag]].\n\nThe Steelers logo was introduced in 1962 and is based on the \"[[Steelmark]]\", originally designed by Pittsburgh's [[U.S. Steel]] and now owned by the [[American Iron and Steel Institute]] (AISI). In fact, it was [[Cleveland]]-based [[Republic Steel]] that suggested the Steelers adopt the industry logo. It consists of the word \"Steelers\" surrounded by three [[astroid]]s ([[hypocycloid]]s of four [[cusp (singularity)|cusps]]). The original meanings behind the astroids were, \"Steel lightens your work, brightens your leisure, and widens your world.\" Later, the colors came to represent the ingredients used in the steel-making process: yellow for coal, red for iron ore, and blue for scrap steel.<ref>{{cite web|title=What Is the Story Behind the Symbol on the Headgear of the Pittsburgh Steelers?|url=http://www.steel.org/Global/document-types/news/2011/what-is-the-story-behind-the-symbol-on-the-headgear-of-the-pittsburgh-steelers.aspx?siteLocation=17d77c91-adc3-4c5b-9158-056d31998ed9|publisher=[[American Iron and Steel Institute]]|date=February 2, 2011|accessdate=May 30, 2016}}</ref> While the formal Steelmark logo contains only the word \"Steel\", the team was given permission to add \"ers\" in 1963 after a petition to AISI.\n\nThe Steelers are the only NFL team that puts its logo on only one side of the helmet (the right side). Longtime field and equipment manager Jack Hart was instructed to do this by Art Rooney as a test to see how the logo appeared on the gold helmets; however, its popularity led the team to leave it that way permanently.<ref>{{cite web|title=History of the Steelers Logo|url=http://www.steelers.com/history/logo-history.html|publisher=Pittsburgh Steelers|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180514184837/http://www.steelers.com/history/logo-history.html|archivedate=May 14, 2018|accessdate=May 18, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> A year after introducing the logo, they switched to black helmets to make it stand out more.\n\nThe Steelers, along with the [[New York Giants]], are one of only two teams in the [[National Football League]] to have the players' uniform numbers on both the front and back of the helmets.\n\nThe current uniform designs were introduced in {{Steelers season|1968}}. The design consists of gold pants and either black jerseys or white jerseys, except for the {{Steelers season|1970}} and {{Steelers season|1971}} seasons when the Steelers wore white pants with their white jerseys. In {{Steelers season|1997}}, the team switched to rounded numbers on the jersey to match the number font ([[Futura Condensed]]) on the helmets, and a Steelers logo was added to the left side of the jersey.\n\nThe 2007\u20132011 third uniform, consisting of a black jersey with gold lettering, white pants with black and gold stripes, and a gold helmet were first used during the Steelers' 75th anniversary season in {{Steelers season|2007}}. They were meant to evoke the memory of the {{Steelers season|1963}}\u2013{{Steelers season|1964}} era uniforms. The uniforms were so popular among fans that the Steelers' organization decided to keep them and use them as a third option during home games only.\n\nIn 2012, the Steelers introduced a new third uniform, consisting of a yellow jersey with black horizontal lines (making a bumble bee like pattern) with black lettering and black numbers placed inside a white box, to represent the jerseys worn by the Steelers in their [[1934 Pittsburgh Pirates (NFL) season|1934 season]]. The rest of the uniform consists of beige pants, yellow with black horizontal stripped socks, and the Steelers regular black helmet. The uniforms were used for the Steelers' 80th anniversary season. Much like the previous alternate these jerseys were so popular that they were used up through the 2016 season. The jerseys were nicknamed the \"bumblebee jerseys\" due to looking like the pattern of a bumble bee. The jerseys were retired after the 2016 season.\n\nIn 2018, the Steelers unveiled a third uniform based on those worn by the Steel Curtain teams of the 1970s. It is similar to the current uniforms but without the Steelers logo on the left chest and use block lettering and numbers in place of Futura Condensed.\n\nIn {{Steelers season|2008}}\u20132009, the Steelers became the first team in NFL history to defeat an opponent three times in a single season using three different uniforms.{{Citation needed|date=November 2009}} They defeated the Baltimore Ravens in Pittsburgh in Week 4 in their third jerseys, again Week 15 in Baltimore in their road whites, and a final time in the AFC Championship in Pittsburgh in their home black jerseys.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baltimoreravens.com/photos/looking-back-on-ravens-steelers-matchups-over-the-years-14123976?campaign=sf:fanshare:facebook|title=Looking Back On Ravens-Steelers Matchups Over The Years|website=www.baltimoreravens.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref>\n\nIn 1979, the team owners were approached by then-[[Iowa Hawkeyes football|Iowa Hawkeyes]] Head Coach [[Hayden Fry]] about designing his fading college team's uniforms in the image of the Steelers. Three days later, the owners sent Fry the reproduction jerseys (home and away versions) of then quarterback [[Terry Bradshaw]]. Today, the Hawkeyes still retain the 1979 Steelers uniforms as their home, and away colors.\n\n== Rivals ==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=July 2013}}\nThe Pittsburgh Steelers have three primary rivals, all within their division: ([[Cleveland Browns]], [[Baltimore Ravens]], and [[Cincinnati Bengals]]). They also have rivalries with other teams that arose from post-season battles in the past, most notably the [[New England Patriots]], [[Oakland Raiders]], [[Tennessee Titans]] and [[Dallas Cowboys]]. They also have an intrastate [[Eagles\u2013Steelers rivalry|rivalry]] with the [[Philadelphia Eagles]], but under the current scheduling the teams play each other only once every four years.\n\n=== Divisional rivals ===\n*The [[Browns\u2013Steelers rivalry|Cleveland Browns and the Steelers]] have been divisional rivals since the two cities' teams began playing against each other in 1950. After posting a 9\u201331 record in the first 40 games of the series between the two cities, the Steelers have gone 66\u201327\u20131 (including 42\u20136 in games played in Pittsburgh) since 1970 and currently lead the series 75\u201358\u20131; The Steelers have particularly dominated the Browns since their return to the NFL in 1999 and won twelve straight meetings between 2003 and 2009.  Additionally, the Browns posted losing streaks of 16 (1970\u201385) and 15 (2004\u2013present) games in Pittsburgh. Former Steelers head coach [[Bill Cowher]] coached the Browns special teams and secondary before following [[Marty Schottenheimer]] for a brief tenure as [[Kansas City Chiefs]] defensive coordinator, and then hired by Pittsburgh. This has only intensified the rivalry. The teams have met twice in the postseason (1994 and 2002) with the Steelers winning both meetings.\n*The [[Ravens\u2013Steelers rivalry|Baltimore Ravens and the Steelers]] have had several memorable match-ups and have a bitter divisional rivalry. Both teams handed the other their first losses at their current home fields. The Steelers won the inaugural game played at [[Baltimore, Maryland|Baltimore's]] [[M&T Bank Stadium]] in {{nfly|1998}}, 20\u201313, and three years later the [[Baltimore Ravens|Ravens]] handed the Steelers their first-ever loss at [[Heinz Field]], 13\u201310. Later that season ({{nfly|2001}}) Pittsburgh won a [[2001\u201302 NFL playoffs#AFC: Pittsburgh Steelers 27, Baltimore Ravens 10|divisional playoff game]] 27\u201310 against Baltimore, who was the [[Super Bowl XXXV|defending Super Bowl champion]]. During their NFL championship season in [[2000 Baltimore Ravens season|2000]], the Ravens defeated the Steelers [[Three Rivers Stadium|in Pittsburgh]], 16\u20130, in the season opener with the Steelers later exacting revenge, 9\u20136, in Baltimore (the Ravens' final loss of the season). During the Steelers 2008 Championship run, they beat the Ravens three times, including a win in the AFC Championship game. The two teams complement each other by consistently fielding strong defenses. The Steelers lead the all-time series (including playoffs), 28\u201324.  The teams have met four times in the postseason, with the Steelers owning a 3\u20131 record.\n*The [[Bengals\u2013Steelers rivalry|Steelers' rivalry with the Cincinnati Bengals]] dates from the {{Steelers season|1970}} season, when the [[AFL\u2013NFL merger]] was completed. In {{Steelers season|1976}}, the Steelers kept their playoff hopes alive (they later won the division) with a late-season 7\u20133 win in snowy Cincinnati. One of the most memorable games was the [[2005\u201306 NFL playoffs#AFC: Pittsburgh Steelers 31, Cincinnati Bengals 17|2005 AFC Wildcard playoff game]], in which the Steelers, en route to a [[Super Bowl XL|Super Bowl title]], won a 31\u201317 come-from-behind victory after [[Cincinnati Bengals|Bengals]] QB [[Carson Palmer]] was forced to leave the game with a knee injury. The injury happened when nose tackle [[Kimo von Oelhoffen]] contacted Palmer's knee during a passing play.  The Bengals players called this a dirty play; the NFL ruled that it was accidental and did not fine von Oelhoffen for the hit.  The incident led to an intensifying of the rivalry. The Bengals beat the Steelers in Week 13 of the {{Steelers season|2005}} season 38\u201331, and wide receiver [[T. J. Houshmandzadeh]] used a [[Terrible Towel]] to polish his cleats while walking up the tunnel after the game, fueling the rivalry. The Steelers and Bengals finished {{nfly|2005}} and {{nfly|2006}} with identical records (11\u20135 and 8\u20138 respectively), splitting both regular-season series, the Bengals winning the tiebreaker both years due to having a superior division record. The Steelers also are responsible for ending the Bengals' season in Cincinnati two years in a row, eliminating them from the playoffs in {{Steelers season|2005}} and taking them out of contention in {{Steelers season|2006}}. The rivalry has become more intense again since the {{Steelers season|2015}} season. A central figure is Bengals linebacker [[Vontaze Burfict]], often inflicting brutal hits, resulting in serious injuries to several Steelers on multiple occasions. In the 2015 Wild Card playoff game in Cincinnati, Burfict was the culprit of a late penalty directly responsible for an extremely unlikely 18-16 Steelers comeback victory. The Steelers lead the all-time series, 63\u201335.  The teams have met twice in the postseason, with the Steelers winning both times.\n\n=== Historic rivals ===\n====Oakland Raiders====\nThe [[Raiders\u2013Steelers rivalry]] was one of the most heated of the 1970s and early to mid-1980s. The Steelers' first playoff win was a 13\u20137 victory over the Raiders by way of [[Franco Harris]]'s [[Immaculate Reception]] on December 23, 1972. The wild card Pittsburgh football team was knocked out of the playoffs the following year by the Raiders in the 1973 AFC Divisional round 33\u201314, but fired back with two straight AFC Championships in {{nfly|1974}} 24\u201313 and {{nfly|1975}} 16\u201310 over Oakland. Oakland responded with a victory over Pittsburgh in the {{nfly|1976}} AFC Championship game 24\u20137 (the third consecutive AFC title game between the two teams), but not before [[Chuck Noll]] referred to Oakland's [[George Atkinson (safety)|George Atkinson]] as part of the NFL's \"criminal element\" after his alleged cheap-shot on [[Lynn Swann]] during a regular-season matchup. Atkinson and the Raiders later filed a [[defamation of character]] [[lawsuit]] against Noll, but lost. Following the 1983 regular season, the Los Angeles Raiders defeated the Steelers 38\u201310 in the AFC Divisional round which turned out to be the last NFL game for Steeler Pro Football Hall of Fame quarterback Terry Bradshaw who did not play due to injury.\n\nWhile the rivalry has dissipated over the years (mostly due to Oakland's decline after [[2002 Oakland Raiders season|2002]]), the teams have had notable games against each other including an upset Steelers victory towards the end of the {{Steelers season|2000}} season to prevent the Raiders from obtaining homefield advantage in the playoffs, and an upset Raiders victory in week 8 of the [[2006 NFL season]] (20\u201313), which helped cost the Steelers a playoff berth. In Week 13 of the 2009 season, another Raiders upset victory happened; the game lead changed five times on five touchdowns in the fourth quarter until Raiders QB [[Bruce Gradkowski]]'s third touchdown of the quarter won it with nine seconds to go. The 27\u201324 loss cost the Steelers another playoff run. The teams met at [[Heinz Field|Pittsburgh]] in {{Steelers season|2010}}, where the Steelers blew out the Raiders 35\u20133, and ended their 3-game winning streak; the game was further notable for a punch thrown by [[Richard Seymour]] of the Raiders against Steelers quarterback [[Ben Roethlisberger]]. The Raiders then hosted the Steelers in [[2012 Oakland Raiders season|2012]] and erased a 31\u201321 gap to win 34\u201331. The two clubs met again in [[2013 NFL season|2013]] and the Raiders won again, 21\u201318. In 2015, the Steelers defeated the Raiders 38\u201335 at Heinz Field. The Steelers trail the all-time series 16\u201313 (13\u201310 in regular season). In their most recent matchup, the Raiders defeated the Steelers 24\u201321 on December 9, 2018 in Oakland, which, ironically, would cost Pittsburgh another playoff berth.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2018/12/09/raiders-block-fg-to-finish-dramatic-upset-of-steelers-24-21/ | title=Raiders Block FG To Finish Dramatic Upset Of Steelers, 24-21 | publisher=CBS San Francisco | work=The Associated Press | date=9 December 2018 | accessdate=19 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Dallas Cowboys====\nThe [[Cowboys\u2013Steelers rivalry]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/blog/dallas-cowboys/post/_/id/4755558/cowboys-steelers-rivalry-has-been-one-for-the-ages|title=Cowboys, Steelers rivalry has been one for the ages|newspaper=ESPN.com|access-date=January 20, 2017}}</ref> started with the Cowboys' first game as a franchise in {{nfly|1960}} (against the Steelers) at the [[Cotton Bowl (stadium)|Cotton Bowl]] with the Steelers coming away with a 35\u201328 victory. These teams hold a record for the most times (three) that two teams have met in a [[Super Bowl]]. The first two times the favored Steelers and Cowboys met came with Pittsburgh victories in the Orange Bowl [[Super Bowl X]] 21\u201317 and [[Super Bowl XIII]] 35\u201331. The Cowboys never won a regular season game in the Orange Bowl and lost three Super Bowl games (once to the Baltimore Colts and twice to the Steelers). Between the Cowboys and Steelers, Super Bowl XIII had the greatest number of future Pro Football Hall of Fame players participating, which as of 2010 numbered 20&nbsp;\u2013 14 players and six coaches/front office, including [[Ernie Stautner]], [[defensive coordinator]] for the Cowboys who was a HoF [[defensive tackle]] for the Steelers. The teams featured an all-star matchup at quarterback between the Steelers' [[Terry Bradshaw]] and the Cowboys' [[Roger Staubach]], both of whom are in the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame]]. In {{nfly|1977}}, Staubach and the Cowboys won [[Super Bowl XII]], their second and last loss of their season being inflicted by Bradshaw and the Steelers, 28\u201313 at Three Rivers Stadium in November. In {{nfly|1979}}, Staubach's final season, the two defending conference champs met again at Three Rivers, the Steelers winning 14\u20133 en route to winning their [[Super Bowl XIV|fourth Super Bowl title]]. The Steelers won six of eight meetings during the 1970s and 80s, before the Cowboys won all four meetings during the 1990s, including the teams' record third Super Bowl meeting in [[Super Bowl XXX|1996]], as this time the heavily favored Cowboys beat the Steelers 27\u201317. Dallas cornerback [[Larry Brown (cornerback)|Larry Brown]] intercepted Pittsburgh quarterback [[Neil O'Donnell]] twice and was named the game's MVP. The teams' first two meetings of the 21st century ({{nfly|2004}} and {{nfly|2008}}) were won by the Steelers, including a come from behind victory December 7, 2008 in Pittsburgh, when the Steelers drove the length of the field to tie the game 13\u201313, then [[cornerback]] [[Deshea Townsend]] returned an intercepted pass from [[Tony Romo]] for the game's final score, Steelers 20, Cowboys 13. The Cowboys won on December 16, 2012, at Cowboys Stadium by a 27\u201324 margin in overtime and won 35-30 at [[Heinz Field]] on November 13, 2016. The all-time series is led by the Dallas Cowboys, 17\u201315. The Pittsburgh/Dallas rivalry served as a backdrop to the 1977 film ''[[Black Sunday (1977 film)|Black Sunday]]'', parts of which were filmed during Super Bowl X. The teams will next play in the regular season in Dallas in 2020.\n\n====Denver Broncos====\nThe [[Denver Broncos]] in 2011 broke a tie with the [[Oakland Raiders]] for the most playoff meetings versus the Steelers and added yet another meeting in 2015 (the Broncos have met Pittsburgh eight times to Oakland's six). The rivalry dates from {{Steelers season|1970}}, but the first notable contest came in {{Steelers season|1973}}, when Denver dealt Pittsburgh its first regular-season defeat at [[Three Rivers Stadium]], 23\u201313. The following year, they met in the NFL's first regular-season overtime game, which ended in a 35\u201335 tie. Denver's first playoff game had them hosting the Steelers in the 1977 divisional round; the Broncos won 34\u201321. The following year, the Steelers hosted and defeated Denver 33\u201310 in the divisional round. Their next playoff matchup was the 1984 divisional round in [[Mile High Stadium]]; the Steelers pulled the upset 24\u201317. They nearly pulled the upset again 5 years later in Denver, but the Broncos prevailed in the divisional playoff, 24\u201323.\n\nIn 1997, the two teams met in [[Pittsburgh]] for the [[AFC Championship Game]], where Denver squeaked out at 24\u201321 win. Eight years later, the Steelers advanced to [[Super Bowl XL]] by beating Denver 34\u201317 in Colorado. In 2011, after appearing in [[Super Bowl XLV]], the Steelers had their campaign to repeat as [[American Football Conference|AFC Champions]] dashed in Denver after a stunning overtime upset by the [[Tim Tebow]]-led Broncos in January 2012, in what would become known as the \"316 game\". The following September the Steelers were defeated in Denver 31\u201319 in [[Peyton Manning]]'s [[2012 Denver Broncos season|debut as Broncos quarterback]]. The two clubs met twice in [[2015 Pittsburgh Steelers season|2015]], as the Steelers defeated the Broncos in the regular season but fell in the Divisional Round of the AFC playoffs; Denver presently leads the series 20\u201311\u20131, including 5\u20133 in the playoffs. Neither team has beaten the other more than three times in a row. In their last matchup, the Broncos beat the Steelers on November 25, 2018 in Denver by the score of 24\u201317.\n\n====New England Patriots====\nThe [[New England Patriots]] emerged as a prominent rival in league circles when the Patriots upset the Steelers in the 2001 [[AFC Championship Game]] at [[Heinz Field]], though the two teams had met in the postseason twice before; the Patriots defeated the Steelers in [[1996 New England Patriots season|1996]] 28-3 while the Steelers won 7-6 in [[1997 Pittsburgh Steelers season|1997]]; both times, the Patriots fielded players with Pittsburgh-area roots in [[Ty Law]] and [[Curtis Martin]]. Martin's final game with the Patriots was in the 1997 playoffs before he departed to the rival [[1998 New York Jets season|New York Jets]]. Following the 2001 AFC title upset, the Patriots defeated the Steelers 30-14 at the start of the 2002 season. Pittsburgh did not exact revenge for the two losses until ending the Patriots' record-setting 21-game winning streak in week 6 of the [[2004 NFL season]]. Later that season, the Steelers lost to the eventual Super Bowl champion Patriots in the AFC Championship game after a 15\u20131 regular season.\n\nThe Patriots won six of seven meetings over a ten-year period ({{nfly|1998}}\u2013{{nfly|2007}}) before the Steelers broke through with a 33\u201310 victory at [[Gillette Stadium|Foxborough]] in {{nfly|2008}}, after [[Matt Cassel]] turned the ball over five times. The Patriots in [[2013 Pittsburgh Steelers season|2013]] then made history by becoming the first opponent to score 55 points on the Steelers, winning 55\u201331. The Patriots won again in 2015 (28-21) and 2016's regular season (27-16), and then won 36-17 in the 2016 [[AFC Championship Game]]. They also won in 2017 when a go-ahead touchdown reception by Steelers' tight end [[Jesse James (tight end)|Jesse James]] was controversially called back.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/jesse-james-overturned-touchdown-latest-example-of-why-fans-hate-nfls-catch-rule/|title = Jesse James' overturned touchdown latest example of why fans hate NFL's catch rule|first = Ryan|last = Wilson|publisher = CBS Sports|date = December 18, 2017|accessdate = July 31, 2018}}</ref> Though they ultimately missed the playoffs, the Steelers defeated the Patriots by a score of 17\u201310 on December 16, 2018 in Pittsburgh.\n\nIn the postseason, the Patriots have outscored the Steelers 135\u201375, with the Patriots maintaining a 4\u20131 record. The only other franchises with winning AFC playoff records against Steelers include the [[Los Angeles Chargers]] (2\u20131), the [[2007 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]] (2\u20130), and the Broncos (5\u20133). The Steelers have an all-time regular-season record of 15\u201313 against the Patriots. In the [[Bill Belichick]] era, the main period of the rivalry, the Patriots have a 12\u20134 record against the Steelers. In their last matchup, the Patriots beat the Steelers 33\u20133 on [[NBC Sunday Night Football|Sunday Night Football]].\n\n====Tennessee Titans====\nLess well known is Pittsburgh's [[Steelers\u2013Titans rivalry|rivalry]] with the [[Tennessee Titans|Houston Oilers/Tennessee Titans]] franchise. The Oilers were aligned into the [[AFC Central]] with the Steelers in 1970 and were division rivals for 32 seasons. The Steelers dominated the rivalry during the Houston era and defeated the Oilers in all three of their playoff matchups. However, since the franchise moved to Tennessee in 1997, the rivalry shifted, with the Titans winning 13 of 22 meetings (including a bitter 34\u201331 playoff showdown in [[2002 Pittsburgh Steelers season|2002]]); the Titans won seven in a row in the 1997\u20132001 period, the longest win streak by either team in the series. The Steelers have won 46 of 78 career meetings following their 40\u201317 win at Heinz Field in 2017. The teams' next regular season match-up will take place in Tennessee in 2020.\n\n== Culture ==\n\n=== Mascot ===\n[[File:SteelyMcBeam.jpg|thumb|right|Steely McBeam signing autographs for fans at Steelers training camp on August 2, 2007]]\nPrior to the {{Steelers season|2007}} season, the Steelers introduced Steely McBeam as their official mascot.<ref name=\"CatchingUp\">{{cite news |first= Robert |last= Dvorchak|title= Catching up with their competitors, the Steelers christen a mascot|url= http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/07221/808167-66.stm |work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|date= August 9, 2007|accessdate=April 27, 2008 }}</ref> As part of the 75th anniversary celebrations of the team, his name was selected from a pool of 70,000 suggestions submitted by fans of the team.<ref name=\"CatchingUp\" /> Diane Roles of [[Middlesex Township, Butler County, Pennsylvania|Middlesex Township]], submitted the winning name which was \"meant to represent steel for Pittsburgh's industrial heritage, \"Mc\" for the Rooney family's Irish roots, and Beam for the steel beams produced in Pittsburgh, as well as for [[Jim Beam]], her husband's favorite alcoholic beverage.\"<ref name=\"Name\">{{cite news |first= Maureen |last= Byko|title= Middlesex grandmother won Steelers 'Name the Mascot' contest|url= http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/07231/810067-54.stm|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date= August 19, 2007 |accessdate=April 27, 2008 }}</ref> Steely McBeam is visible at all home games and participates in the team's charitable programs and other club-sponsored events.<ref name=\"CatchingUp\" /> Steely's autograph is known to be drawn with an oversized ''S'', and the ''L'' is drawn to look like a beam of steel.<ref name=\"CatchingUp\" />\n\n=== Fanbase ===\n{{Main|Steeler Nation}}\nThe Steelers have a tradition of having a large fanbase, which has spread from Pittsburgh. In August 2008, [[ESPN.com]] ranked the Steelers' fans as the best in the NFL, citing their \"unbelievable\" sellout streak of 299&nbsp;consecutive games.<ref name=\"Mosley\" /><ref>{{cite news |title= ESPN ranks Steelers fans No. 1|url= http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/sports/steelers/s_585606.html?source=rss&feed=3|newspaper=Pittsburgh Tribune-Review|date= August 30, 2008|accessdate=August 30, 2008}}</ref> The team gained a large fan base nationally based on its success in the 1970s, but many consider the collapse of the city's steel industry at the end of the 1970s dynasty into the 1980s (and the resulting [[diaspora]]) to be a large catalyst for the size of the fan base in other cities.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} The Steelers have sold out every home game since the {{Steelers season|1972}} season.<ref name=CopeDeath>{{cite news |agency=Associated Press|authorlink= Associated Press|title= Steelers' former radio announcer Myron Cope dies at 79|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/steelers/2008-02-27-cope-obit_N.htm |work=USA Today|date= February 28, 2008|accessdate=June 7, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe Pittsburgh Steelers have numerous unofficial fan clubs in many cities throughout the country, that typically meet in bars or taverns on game days.  This phenomenon is known to occur for other NFL teams as well, but \"Steeler bars\" are more visible than most, including representative establishments even in cities that field their own NFL teams.\n[[File:US Navy 090202-N-5253W-043 Sailors and Marines aboard the amphibious assault ship USS Essex (LHD 2) react as the Pittsburgh Steelers score against the Arizona Cardinals late in the fourth quarter of Superbowl XLIII.jpg|thumb|Sailors and Marines aboard the USS ''Essex'' react as the Pittsburgh Steelers score against the Arizona Cardinals.]]\nThe [[Terrible Towel]] has been described by the Associated Press as \"arguably the best-known [[rally towel|fan symbol]] of any major pro sports team\".<ref name=CopeDeath /> Conceived of by broadcaster [[Myron Cope]] in {{Steelers season|1975}},<ref name=CopeDeath /> the towel's rights have since been given to the Allegheny Valley School in [[Coraopolis, Pennsylvania|Coraopolis]], which cares for over 900 people with [[intellectual disability]] and [[Disability|physical disabilities]], including Cope's [[Autism|autistic]] son.<ref name=AVSchool>{{cite web| title = Allegheny Valley School Mourns the Loss of Myron Cope| publisher=Allegheny Valley School| date = February 27, 2008| url = http://www.avs.net/terribletowel.cfm| accessdate = February 29, 2008| archivedate = May 11, 2008| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080511235240/http://www.avs.net/terribletowel.cfm}}</ref> Since 1996, proceeds from the Terrible Towel have helped raise more than $2.5 million for the school.<ref name=AVSchool />\n\n=== Fight songs ===\nThe Steelers have no official fight song, but many fan versions of ''Here we go Steelers'' and the ''Steelers Polka'' (the latter a parody of ''[[Pennsylvania Polka]]'') by ethnic singer Jimmy Pol, both originating in the 1970s, have been recorded. Since 1994, the song ''[[Here We Go (Steelers song)|Here We Go]]'' by local singer Roger Wood has been popular among fans.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} During Steelers games, [[Styx (band)|Styx]]'s ''[[Renegade (Styx song)|Renegade]]'' is often used to rally the crowd.\n\n=== Basketball ===\nDuring the offseason, the Steelers have long participated in charity [[basketball]] games throughout [[Western Pennsylvania]] and neighboring areas. The games usually feature six active players as well as their [[player-coach]] playing against a group of local civic leaders.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vindy.com/news/2012/mar/12/steelers-to-play-basketball-in-poland/ |title=Youngstown News, Steelers to play basketball in Poland |publisher=Vindy.com |date=March 12, 2012 |accessdate=September 3, 2012}}</ref> The players, whose participants aren't announced until the day of the game, sign free autographs for fans during halftime.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goerie.com/article/20120322/SPORTS13/303219886/Steelers-to-play-basketball-game-April-22-at-Behrend |title=Steelers to play basketball game April 22 at Behrend &#124; GoErie.com/Erie Times-News |publisher=Goerie.com |date= |accessdate=September 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Facilities ==\n\n=== Stadiums ===\n{{unreferenced section|date=June 2017}}\nIn 2001, the Steelers moved into [[Heinz Field]]. The franchise dating back to 1933 has had several homes. For 31 seasons, the Steelers shared [[Forbes Field]] with the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] from 1933 to 1963. In 1958, though they started splitting their home games at [[Pitt Stadium]] three blocks away at the [[University of Pittsburgh]]. From 1964 to 1969, the Steelers played exclusively at the on campus facility before moving with the Pirates to [[Three Rivers Stadium]] on the city's [[Northside (Pittsburgh)|Northside]]. Three Rivers is remembered fondly by the Steeler Nation as where Chuck Noll and Dan Rooney turned the franchise into a powerhouse, winning four Super Bowls in just six seasons and making the playoffs 11 times in 13 seasons from 1972 to 1984, the AFC title game seven times. Since 2001 however a new generation of Steeler greats has made Heinz Field legendary with multiple AFC Championship Games being hosted and two Super Bowl championships.\n\n=== Training camp ===\n[[File:Steelerstrainingcamp.jpg|thumb|210px|Steelers at training camp in Latrobe]]\n\nThe Steelers hold [[Training camp (National Football League)|training camp]] east of the city at [[Saint Vincent College]] in [[Latrobe, Pennsylvania|Latrobe]]. The site is one of the most storied in the league with [[Peter King (sportswriter)|Peter King]] of SI.com describing it as: \"... I love the place. It's the perfect training-camp setting, looking out over the rolling hills of the [[Laurel Highlands]] in [[Western Pennsylvania|west-central Pennsylvania]], an hour east of Pittsburgh. On a misty or foggy morning, standing atop the hill at the college, you feel like you're in [[Scotland]]. Classic, wonderful slice of [[Americana]]. If you can visit one training camp, this is the one to see.''<ref>{{cite news|last=King|first=Peter|title=Postcard from camp: Steelers|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2010/writers/peter_king/08/20/steelers.postcard/index.html|magazine=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=August 20, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821162023/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2010/writers/peter_king/08/20/steelers.postcard/index.html|archivedate=August 21, 2010|accessdate=May 18, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe team has its headquarters and practice facilities at the state-of-the-art [[UPMC Sports Performance Complex|University of Pittsburgh Medical Center Sportsplex]] on Pittsburgh's [[Southside (Pittsburgh)|Southside]]. Constructed in 2000, the facility combines the vast expertise of sports medical professionals and researchers as well as hosting the [[University of Pittsburgh Panthers]] football team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tour.pitt.edu/tour/southside-sports-complex-upmc-sports-performance-complex|title=Southside Sports Complex (UPMC Sports Performance Complex) {{!}} Campus Tour|website=www.tour.pitt.edu|access-date=October 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Historical facilities ===\nThe Rooney family has long had a close relationship with [[Duquesne University]] in the city and from the teams founding in the 1930s to the late 1990s used [[Arthur J. Rooney Athletic Field|Art Rooney Field]] and other facilities on campus as either its primary or secondary in-season training site as well as [[Greenlee Field]] during the 1930s.<ref>{{cite news|title=Eagles Due Today for Pirate Game|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=J7VRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=K2kDAAAAIBAJ&dq=mcnally%20pittsburgh&pg=2384%2C2841237|newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=September 25, 1934|accessdate=May 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1970s and 1980s, the team had season scrimmages at [[South Park Township|South Park]] in the [[Pittsburgh metropolitan area|suburban south hills]] of Pittsburgh.  During various seasons including the [[1987 NFL season|strike season]] of 1987, the Steelers used [[Point Stadium]] in nearby [[Johnstown, Pennsylvania|Johnstown]] for game week practices.<ref>''[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=djft3U1LymYC&dat=19870924&printsec=frontpage]'', ''Pittsburgh Press Sep 24, 1987</ref>  During the 1950s [[St. Bonaventure University]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Graham|first=Tim|title=Butler recalls when Steelers cut Unitas at St. Bona|url=http://blogs.buffalonews.com/press-coverage/2012/08/butler-recalls-when-steelers-cut-unitas-at-st-bona.html|newspaper=[[The Buffalo News]]|date=August 3, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120805035241/http://blogs.buffalonews.com/press-coverage/2012/08/butler-recalls-when-steelers-cut-unitas-at-st-bona.html|archivedate=August 5, 2012|accessdate=May 18, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> and suburban [[Ligonier, Pennsylvania|Ligonier]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Steelers Get All Shook Up|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=MBxiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=p3UNAAAAIBAJ&dq=steelers%20jacksonville&pg=4264%2C756988|newspaper=The Washington Reporter|date=September 10, 1957|accessdate=May 18, 2018}}</ref> also served as a pre-season training camp sites.\n\n== Statistics ==\n{{Further|Pittsburgh Steelers statistics}}\n\n== Players of note ==\n{{Main|List of Pittsburgh Steelers players}}\n\n=== Current roster ===\n{{Pittsburgh Steelers roster}}\n\n=== Retired uniform numbers ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n| colspan=6 style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers}};\"| '''Pittsburgh Steelers retired numbers'''\n|-\n!  style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers}};\"|No.\n!  style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers}};\"|Player\n!  style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers}};\"|Position\n!  style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers}};\"|Seasons\n!  style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers}};\"|Retired\n!  style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers}};\"|Ref.\n|-\n| '''70''' || [[Ernie Stautner]] || [[Defensive tackle|DT]] || 1950\u20131963 || October 25, 1964 || <ref>{{cite news|last=Silver|first=Alexandra|title=Only One Retired Number|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2046387_2046389_2046479,00.html|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=February 4, 2011|accessdate=May 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| '''75''' || [[Joe Greene (American football)|Joe Greene]] || [[Defensive tackle|DT]] || 1969\u20131981 || November 2, 2014 ||<ref>{{cite news|title=Pittsburgh Steelers to Retire Joe Greene's Number '75'|url=http://www.steelers.com/news/article-1/Pittsburgh-Steelers-to-Retire-Joe-Greenes-Number-75/0a9e49b0-97db-4c90-9a5d-a486ed8f7889|publisher=Pittsburgh Steelers|date=July 30, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140801035157/http://www.steelers.com/news/article-1/Pittsburgh-Steelers-to-Retire-Joe-Greenes-Number-75/0a9e49b0-97db-4c90-9a5d-a486ed8f7889|archivedate=August 1, 2014|accessdate=May 18, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|}\n\nThe Steelers retired Stautner's #70 in 1964 before creating a 50-year tradition of not retiring numbers. The team retired Greene's #75 in 2014 and left the possibility open that they would retire other players' jersey numbers at later dates. Other numbers are no longer issued since the retirement of the players who wore them, including:<ref>{{cite book|title=Pittsburgh Steelers Glory Days|first=Dale|last=Grdnic|isbn=978-1-61321-329-2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bkMtAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT62|date=August 2013}}</ref>\n\n*'''1''' [[Gary Anderson (placekicker)|Gary Anderson]]\n*'''12''' [[Terry Bradshaw]]\n*'''32''' [[Franco Harris]]\n*'''36''' [[Jerome Bettis]]\n*'''43''' [[Troy Polamalu]]\n*'''47''' [[Mel Blount]]\n*'''52''' [[Mike Webster]]\n*'''58''' [[Jack Lambert (American football)|Jack Lambert]]\n*'''59''' [[Jack Ham]]\n*'''63''' [[Dermontti Dawson]]\n*'''86''' [[Hines Ward]]\n\n=== Pro Football Hall of Famers ===\n\n==== \"Primary\" inductees ====\nThe Steelers boast the third most \"primary\" [[List of Pro Football Hall of Fame inductees|inductees]] into the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]], i.e. inductees that spent most or all of their NFL careers in Pittsburgh.  They also can claim the most honorees of any franchise founded on or after {{nfly|1933}} and the only franchise with three members of ownership in the Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"profootballhof1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/teams.html|title=Teams \u2013 Pro Football Hall of Fame Official Site|website=www.profootballhof.com}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! colspan=6 style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers}}; text-align:center;\"|Pittsburgh Steelers Hall of Famers \n|-\n! colspan=6 style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers}}; text-align:center;\"|Players\n|-\n! No.\n! Name\n! Inducted\n! Position(s)\n! Years w/ Steelers\n! Ref.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 36 ||<span style=\"display:none\">Bettis, Jerome</span>'''[[Jerome Bettis]]''' || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2015 || [[Running back|RB]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{Steelers season|1996}}\u2013{{Steelers season|2005}} ||<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/member.jsp?PLAYER_ID=296|title=Jerome Bettis \u2013 Pro Football Hall of Fame Official Site|website=www.profootballhof.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 47 ||<span style=\"display:none\">Blount, Mel</span>'''[[Mel Blount]]''' || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1989  || [[Cornerback|CB]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{Steelers season|1970}}\u2013{{Steelers season|1983}} ||<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/member.jsp?PLAYER_ID=30|title=Mel Blount \u2013 Pro Football Hall of Fame Official Site|website=www.profootballhof.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 12 ||<span style=\"display:none\">Bradshaw, Terry</span>'''[[Terry Bradshaw]]''' || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1989 || [[Quarterback|QB]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{Steelers season|1970}}\u2013{{Steelers season|1983}} ||<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/member.jsp?player_id=31|title=Terry Bradshaw \u2013 Pro Football Hall of Fame Official Site|website=www.profootballhof.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 80 ||<span style=\"display:none\">Butler, Jack</span>'''[[Jack Butler (American football)|Jack Butler]]''' || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2012 || [[Cornerback|CB]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{Steelers season|1951}}\u2013{{Steelers season|1959}} ||<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/member.jsp?player_id=305|title=Jack Butler \u2013 Pro Football Hall of Fame Official Site|website=www.profootballhof.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 63 ||<span style=\"display:none\">Dawson, Dermontti</span>'''[[Dermontti Dawson]]'''|| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2012 || [[Center (American football)|C]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{Steelers season|1988}}\u2013{{Steelers season|2000}} ||<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/member.jsp?player_id=275|title=Dermontti Dawson \u2013 Pro Football Hall of Fame Official Site|website=www.profootballhof.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 35 ||<span style=\"display:none\">Dudley, Bill</span>'''[[Bill Dudley]]''' || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1966 || [[Running back|RB]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{Steelers season|1942}}, {{Steelers season|1945}}\u2013{{Steelers season|1946}} ||<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/member.jsp?player_id=61|title=Bill Dudley \u2013 Pro Football Hall of Fame Official Site|website=www.profootballhof.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 75 ||<span style=\"display:none\">Greene, Joe</span>'''[[Joe Greene (American football)|\"Mean\" Joe Greene]]''' || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1987 || [[Defensive tackle|DT]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{Steelers season|1969}}\u2013{{Steelers season|1981}} ||<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/member.jsp?player_id=80|title=Joe Greene \u2013 Pro Football Hall of Fame Official Site|website=www.profootballhof.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-ali